<p>Under tort law, <strong>NEGLIGENCE</strong> is a failure to exercise that degree of care that a reasonable prudent person would use in the same situation. To prevail the plaintiff must usually prove <strong>DUTY</strong>, <strong>BREACH</strong>, <strong>ACTUAL</strong> and <strong>PROXIMATE CAUSATION</strong> and <strong>DAMAGES</strong>.</p>
<p>If Plaintiff can prove the elements of a <strong>prima facie case of negligence</strong> Defandant may be <strong>liable</strong>. </p>
